post_text: What an incredible 1st day of school. Thank you to our families for your patience, understanding, and willingness to allow us to try something new. Our staff worked incredibly hard over the last several months, preparing for whatever was to come. Teaching and supporting classrooms is much more than just academics, and we are so appreciative for you allowing us to fill our buckets today by reconnecting with your children. Please know that we will continue to work non-stop to provide the best educational experience for our students and families. #bobcatnation

post_text: The Boys & Girls Club in Bay City will be open after Labor Day on a daily basis from 8-4 for all kids. Additionally, on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday it will be open from 5-8 for teens. Their goal is to help the kids with their school work and be an extra support for parents who need to work. They can safely take 100 kids because of the bingo hall and the back conference room. They will take kids on a "first come first serve basis" until they reach 100. Their fee for a membership is $25 and it runs through December. If a student qualifies, they can scholarship him/her in. If you have any other questions, please let them know. Their contact number for parents is 989-892-6723.

post_text: Over the past twelve years, my four children have been students within the Bangor Twp. School District. Their mission is to imagine, inspire and innovate. Bangor Township Schools offer an exemplary core curriculum. We don’t reside in the Bangor school district, as we are a “school of choice” family. We were looking for a school that offered academics, extra-curricular activities, sports and leadership. The Bangor Schools provide an environment that enriches, inspires, and challenges students. They are more than a school - they are a community that prepares and develops responsible, kind and resourceful adults. M. Dinauer

With five years of experience in helping students develop personalized education plans that have set them up for success, BTVS has led the way in the Great Lakes Bay Region. If you are uncertain about your child's education for the fall, or if you want to explore all your options, give us a call today or visit our website for more information. Watch the video below for a preview of what we have to offer. #bobcatnation

post_text: Congratulations Blake. You are a true leader in and out of the classroom. We are So very proud of you.
shared_text:
John Glenn Athletics #BobcatNation
April 16 at 11:04 AM ·

The JGHS Athletic Department is proud to announce the 2019-20 recipient of the Saginaw Valley League Male Scholar Athlete of the Year Award - BLAKE WAIBEL!

In his words - "My favorite memory at Glenn was winning districts my sophomore year against Freeland. We battled all season with a very young team playing in the SVL for the first year. We had many tough losses and made many mistakes, but it payed off during the playoffs because we played through adversity all season.

Being a student athlete has taught me values like diligence, responsibility, and perseverance. It takes a lot of time to master a craft, and I’m proud that the work I have put both in the classroom and on the field has paid off.

My future plans are to go to college in the fall to become an engineer, and I will decide where in the next few weeks."

Coach Hartt remarked - "Blake puts "Team" first and Blake is truly a SCHOLAR/ATHLETE."

Are you part of Michigan's essential workforce? Do you need childcare so you can serve our community?

Essential workers in need of emergency childcare can fill out this survey to get connected with a local provider: http://www.helpmegrow-mi.org/essential

Essential workers as defined by the Governor's executive order are: Health care workers, home health workers, direct care workers, emergency medical service providers, first responders, law enforcement personnel, sanitation workers, childcare workers, correctional workers, postal workers, public health employees, key government employees such as child protective services and foster care workers, court personnel, and others providing key infrastructure to Michiganders such as utilities, mass transit, manufacturing, and groceries.

post_text: Please, please, please do your part - other lives could depend on it. Students - stop gathering in groups and visiting each others homes - STAY HOME. There is a reason we are not in school right now, and its because this is real and may get worse if we all don't do our part. While you might not think you will become infected, if you do you will put many other lives at risk. This is a time to think bigger than yourself - the ones you love, as well as our community, are counting on you. Be safe and please listen to what I am telling you. We love you and want to see everyone back in school when we are allowed to return. Mr. Schmidt #bobcatnation

post_text: Congrats to our own Delaney Wesolek!
shared_text:
Bay Area Community Foundation
January 13 at 7:57 PM ·

"Building community starts with me," says Delaney Wesolek. "The vision of Dr. King is alive in me, and I will continue to grow as an adult who values the importance of serving one's community."
.
Delaney is a recipient of the Martin Luther King, Jr. Regional Scholarship that will be presented on January 22. She believes that the root of improving racial harmony and social justice stems from connecting people and communicating.
.
She has done this through volunteering at the The Bay County Historical Society/The Historical Museum of Bay County, serving as class president at her high school and being a leader by connecting and encouraging classmates, and becoming a member of the Youth Advisory Committee-Bay Area Community Foundation to grow and develop the community through projects that impact today's youth.
.
More information about the scholarship reception and celebration at svsu.edu/mlk

post_text:
A huge THANK YOU goes out to the students and staff at John Glenn High School who participated in “The Amazing Race” last week to help raise funds to help send food home to some of our families for Thanksgiving and throughout the year. Through their generous support, we were able to raise
$1,553.64. This money helped us provide 8 Thanksgiving meals for some of our families. The funds raised will also be used for our Bobcat Pantry to help families in need throughout the school year.

A huge THANK YOU also goes out to the John Glenn Student Senate who organized and ran “The Amazing Race” event, Ms. Erica Staudacher and Mrs. Sara Engelberts who helped with shopping and coordination, the Counseling staff at John Glenn for working with our families, and Dr. Austin Collier from Collier Chiropractic for donating all the turkeys for this project. #bobcatnation
